    <fr:title text="Syntax and Semantics">Syntax and Semantics</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Discussion</fr:taxon>
    <fr:authors />
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Mathematics is hard to define, especially the act of "doing" mathematics, but we can represent it in broad strokes by discussing <fr:em>syntax</fr:em> and <fr:em>semantics</fr:em>.</fr:p>
    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:anchor>324</fr:anchor>
        <fr:addr type="user">syntax</fr:addr>
        <fr:route>syntax.xml</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="Syntax">Syntax</fr:title>
        <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:p>Let's say we have some object which the working mathematician has just started to study. The mathematician has some intuitive understanding of how the object works, but they want to study the object in a formal, mathematical manner. As a start, they invent some notation for depicting the object on paper (or a computer screen, or whatever else). Next, using whatever language they are most comfortable in -- be that a natural language or some more formal notation -- they write down the <fr:em>properties</fr:em> they expect the object to satisfy.</fr:p>
        <fr:p>What I have just described is a mathematician creating a <fr:strong>syntax</fr:strong>. A syntax represents a surface-level and literal understanding of an object being studied. It represents how the object is used, observed, and manipulated in everyday practice -- it conveys only what is immediately apparent and obvious about the object and nothing more. This is an <fr:em>essential</fr:em> purpose, and it is exactly one half of the picture that <fr:link type="local" href="semantics.xml" addr="semantics" title="Semantics">semantics</fr:link> completes.</fr:p>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:anchor>325</fr:anchor>
        <fr:addr type="user">semantics</fr:addr>
        <fr:route>semantics.xml</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="Semantics">Semantics</fr:title>
        <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:p>Previously, the working mathematician started studying some object, and developed a <fr:link type="local" href="syntax.xml" addr="syntax" title="Syntax">syntax</fr:link> for it. Now this mathematician has been studying the object for a good while. They have a good idea of what properties the object satisfies and how it works, but they want a deeper understanding. The problem that this mathematician faces is that their syntax is a <fr:em>walled garden</fr:em>. Their invented notation and axioms makes sense to them, but only to them! How is anyone else supposed to understand what it is that they are studying?</fr:p>
        <fr:p>Realizing this, the mathematician talks with their colleagues and starts to draw analogies to established areas of math that their colleagues are more familiar with. "Oh, my object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, but with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> removed", or "You see, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is just like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> if you convert <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(e)]]></fr:tex>", or "Actually, the property <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is really just like your property <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex>".</fr:p>
        <fr:p>Slowly through these analogies, everyone comes to an understanding about what exactly our mathematician has developed. These analogies are what mathematicians call <fr:strong>semantics</fr:strong>, and they are the other half of the picture that <fr:link type="local" href="syntax.xml" addr="syntax" title="Syntax">syntax</fr:link> starts. If syntax represents the intuitive, surface-level, and somewhat trivial understanding of an object, semantics represents the deep and nontrivial understanding of the object <fr:em>in terms of</fr:em> other, more established mathematical objects.</fr:p>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:mainmatter>
